                            </objectDesc>
                            <handDesc>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-1">Gothic hybrida. </handNote>
                            </handDesc>
                            <additions>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Bottom of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Alexander Pauli filius Petauius senator Parisiensis 1649</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1v" to="146r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Copious marginal additions by several hands. Examples: On <locus from="2v" to="2v" scheme="folios"/> there are Bible references in the same ink as the main text and corrections in a darker ink, both appear to be by the scribe or a contemporary hand. This type of additions appear throughout the entire manuscript. From <locus from="4v" to="4v" scheme="folios"/> on additions by an early modern hand start to appear. From <locus from="64v" to="128v" scheme="folios"/> on chapter references by a modern hand in pencil.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="Note_1r" to="Note_1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>An note attached by the scribe or a contemporary hand. It contains 8 lines from Jerome's Commentary on Osee (<bibl>
                                            <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107168">PL</title>
                                            <citedRange from="25" to="25" unit="volume"/>
                                            <citedRange from="879" to="879" unit="column"/>
                                        </bibl>).</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="152v" to="152v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>The entire leaf is covered by two layers of additions. Layer 1: an older medieval hand has written scattered phrases which can be read from two directions, e.g. the phrase <quote>lach lieb lach</quote>. Layer 2: a later medieval hand has covered most of the page with references to and excerpts from different books of the Bible and the Church Fathers. The first line of these additions read: <quote>Sermo feria 3<hi rend="super">a</hi> penthecostes Anno domini 1513</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                            </additions>
                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in black ink, rubrics in red, capitals touched in red, pilcrows in red, green, and blue.</p>
                                <decoNote type="initials">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="1va" to="145va" scheme="folios"/>: The majority of the sermons are opened by plain initials over 2-3 lines alternating in red and green with flourishing in contrasting colour. Some of the initials feature more complex flourishing, e.g. <locus from="109ra" to="109ra" scheme="folios"/> where a face has been drawn in the counterspace (similarily on <locus from="145va" to="145va" scheme="folios"/>). Around ten sermons feature larger plain initials over 5-7 lines, some of these have reserved interior space or complex flourishing, e.g. on <locus from="84va" to="84va" scheme="folios"/>. <locus from="49rb" to="49rb" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="50vb" to="50vb" scheme="folios"/>: two puzzle intitials over 3-5 lines in blue and green with red flourishing. <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>: space reserved for intial. The space reserved extends over 8 lines, but above more than half the leaf is left blank, which may indicate further
                                        decoration was intended.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                            </decoDesc>
